1. e4 1... e5 2. d4 $1 {Chapter: Center Game} 2... exd4 (2... d6 {I DONT recommend dxe5, which will likely lead to a queen trade, which, while favorable, results in a dry game.} 3. Nf3 (3. Bc4 $6 {Could lead to an early bishop sacrifice for the queen.} 3... Nf6 (3... exd4 4. c3 4... dxc3 5. Qb3 5... Qe7 6. Nxc3) (3... Be6 4. Bxe6 (4. d5 {Alright, technically a move, by why close the center if you're going to play the Danish gambit?}) 4... fxe6 5. dxe5 5... dxe5) 4. dxe5 (4. Bxf7+ $6 {Horribly unsound, but somehow every line wins for white.} 4... Kxf7 5. dxe5 5... Nxe4 6. Qd5+) (4. Nf3 {Chapter: Philidor Defense: Nimzowitsch Variation, Klein Variation}) 4... dxe5 (4... Nxe4 5. Qd5 $1 {A lot more testing than Qf3}) 5. Bxf7+ 5... Kxf7 6. Qxd8) (3. dxe5 {While favorable, it usually leads to a queen trade and a dry endgame.}) 3... Nc6 4. Bb5 {My favorite response: Keeps tension on the board, allowing for the possibility of an open position.} (4. d5 {The most principled move, but a bit dry for a gambiteer.}) 4... Bd7 5. d5 5... Nd4 6. Bxd7+ 6... Qxd7 7. Nxd4 7... exd4 8. Qxd4) (2... f6 $4 {Punish this weakening move by taking immediately} 3. dxe5 3... fxe5 4. Qh5+ 4... g6 5. Qxe5+ 5... Qe7 6. Qxh8) (2... Nc6 3. d5 3... Nd4 $5 4. c3 $1) (2... Nf6 3. dxe5) 3. c3 $2 {Chapter: Danish Gambit

You have just entered the Danish Gambit} 3... dxc3 (3... d5 $1 {Chapter: Danish Gambit Declined: Sörensen Defense

Perhaps the most challenging response to the danish gambit. Played rarely below 2000.} 4. exd5 (4. Qb3 $6 {An objectively unsound response to d5, keeping in the spirit of the Danish gambit. There are a lot of ways black can go wrong. I wouldn't necessarily play it against a strong opponent.} 4... dxe4 (4... dxc3 {Surprisingly, some opponents will still accept the prior gambit.} 5. Nf3 (5. Nxc3 {This time, you should probably immediately develop with the knight. We've already pushed our luck to the breaking point.} 5... d4 $1 6. Bc4 $3 {The opponent expects to gain tempo attacking your knight, only to be met with an unsavory surprise.} 6... dxc3 (6... Qe7 7. Nd5 7... Qxe4+ 8. Ne2 8... Qxg2 (8... Bd6 9. O-O) 9. Rg1 9... Qxh2 10. Bf4 $1 {A dazzling line full of pandemonium; black thinks they are getting free material, but you've simelatanously set up a fork on c6, a potential checkmate attack, and an attack on the queen.}) 7. Bxf7+ 7... Ke7 8. Bxg8 8... Rxg8 9. Bg5+ 9... Ke8 10. Bxd8) 5... cxb2 (5... dxe4 {This move seems so natural, yet it immediately cedes black's advantage.} 6. Ng5 {the same attack, but now with the knight. Threatening checkmate.} 6... Nh6 (6... Qe7 7. Nxc3) 7. Bc4) 6. Bxb2 6... dxe4 7. Bc4 7... Qe7 8. O-O 8... exf3 9. Nd2 9... fxg2 10. Rfe1 10... Qxe1+ 11. Rxe1+) (4... Nf6 5. e5 $1 5... Ne4 (5... Qe7 6. cxd4) 6. cxd4 6... Nc6 7. Bb5 (7. Nf3)) (4... Be6 5. Qxb7 5... Nd7 6. Nf3 {Your knight attacks the weak d4 pawn. No matter how they try to defend, you can check the king with your queen or bishop to win material.}) (4... Nc6 5. exd5) 5. Bc4 5... Qe7 (5... Qf6 6. Nh3 (6. Ne2 6... d3 7. Ng3 {This seems cramped and uncomfortable, but the knight immediately attacks the e4 pawn. and threatens to gain tempo on the queen. The only move that keeps black's advantage is Qg6.} 7... Bc5 $2 {Black foolishly attempts a checkmate attack} (7... Bf5 $2 {Black plays Bf5, hoping to protect their pawn.} 8. Qxb7 8... Qc6 9. Bb5 9... Qxb5 10. Qxb5+) (7... Qe7) 8. Nxe4 $6 {A surprisingly common blunder, attempting to checkmate our king.} (8. O-O {Castling is also fine.}) 8... Bxf2+ (8... Qe7) 9. Kf1 {Kf1 instead of kxf2. Knight maintains pressure on the Queen.}) (6. cxd4) 6... Bxh3 (6... h6 7. Nd2 7... e3 8. fxe3 8... dxe3 9. Ne4) (6... Nc6 7. Ng5 $1 7... Nh6 8. Nxe4 {If black defends accurately, you take the pawn and win tempo on the queen.}) 7. Qxb7 7... Bxg2 (7... Qc6 8. Bb5 8... Qxb5 9. Qxb5+) 8. Qxa8 8... Bxh1 9. Bb5+ (9. Qxb8+) 9... c6 (9... Ke7 10. Qxb8) 10. Qxb8+ 10... Qd8 11. Bxc6+ 11... Ke7 12. Qe5# $1) (5... Qd7 6. f3 {An absurdly unsound sideline where you offer your f3 pawn in the hopes of developing with nxf3. If the gambit is accepted, your practical winning chances are very high.} (6. Nd2) (6. Nh3) 6... exf3 (6... e3 {After the most common move, the game is equal.} 7. cxd4) 7. Nxf3 7... dxc3 8. Nxc3 {Shockingly, the second most common response is to accept both gambits, giving you monstrous attacking chances.} 8... Nf6 9. O-O (9. Ng5 9... Qe7+ 10. Kf1 10... Nc6 11. Bxf7+) 9... Bc5+ 10. Kh1) (5... Be6 $4 {White blunders at least two pawns.} 6. Bxe6 6... fxe6 7. Qxb7 7... Qd5 (7... Nd7 8. Qxe4) 8. Qc8+ 8... Kf7 (8... Ke7 9. Qxc7+) 9. Qxc7+) (5... dxc3 6. Bxf7+ 6... Ke7 (6... Kd7 7. Qe6#) 7. Bxg8 7... Rxg8 8. Bg5+ 8... Ke8 9. Bxd8) (5... Nh6 $4 6. Bxh6 6... gxh6 7. Bxf7+) 6. Nh3 (6. Ne2 6... d3 7. Ng3 7... Nf6 8. Bg5 (8. O-O) 8... h6 9. Bxf6 9... Qxf6 10. Nxe4) (6. cxd4 {While not in the spirit of the gambit, taking the pawn is appealing enough to abandon typical gambit ideas.} 6... Nc6 7. Ne2 {Ne2 is important because the queen controls g5.}) 6... Bxh3 $4 (6... Nc6 7. O-O 7... Na5 8. Qa4+ 8... Nc6 9. Ng5 9... Nh6 10. Re1 {You threaten the weak e4 pawn. If the rook is allowed to take, it could pin the queen.} 10... f5 11. Bf4 {your pieces are strangling the opponent's position, and their queen is overworked.}) 7. Qxb7 7... Bxg2 8. Qc8+ (8. Rg1) (8. Qxa8) 8... Qd8 9. Bxf7+ 9... Kxf7 10. Qxd8 10... Bxh1 11. Qd5+ 11... Ke7 12. Qxa8) 4... Qxd5 (4... Nf6 5. Bb5+ {if white delays taking the pawn with the queen, this is the best response.} (5. Nf3 5... Qxd5 6. cxd4) 5... c6 (5... Bd7 6. Bc4 {This move halts black's plans of taking the center. They must play accurately to hold their advantage.} 6... dxc3 7. Nxc3) (5... Nbd7 6. Qxd4) 6. dxc6 6... bxc6 7. Bc4) 5. cxd4 {The game is now equal. Develop kingside first and get your king to safety. Practically, white still wins this position more often than losing it.} 5... Nc6 6. Nf3 6... Bg4 7. Be2 7... Bb4+ (7... Bxf3 8. Bxf3 8... Qxd4 $4 {Queen takes pawn, expecting to be a pawn up after the trades.} 9. Bxc6+ $1 {bxc6!}) 8. Nc3 8... Bxf3 9. Bxf3 9... Qc4 10. Qb3 $1 {You can meet Qc4 with Qb3, but it might limit your attacking chances.} (10. Bxc6+ 10... Qxc6 11. O-O) 10... Qxb3 11. axb3 11... Nxd4 12. Bxb7 12... Rb8 13. Rxa7 {an important exchange to remember.}) (3... Qe7 4. cxd4 4... Qxe4+ 5. Be3 5... Nf6 (5... Bb4+ 6. Nc3 6... Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 7... Nf6 8. Nf3 8... O-O 9. Bd3) 6. Nc3 6... Bb4 7. Nf3 7... Nd5 8. Qd2 8... Nxe3 9. fxe3 9... Qe7 10. Bd3) (3... Nc6 4. Bc4 {A spirited response to Nc6. You allow Nxe4 with the hopes of creating an attack. Not necessarily recommended.} (4. Nf3 {Chapter: Scotch Game: Göring Gambit

When black develops nc6, an early Bc4 might run into ...Nf6, ...Nxe4, or other related knightmares.} 4... Nf6 5. e5 5... Ne4 6. Qe2) (4. cxd4 {A viable capture. Not in the spirit of the Danish, but more realistic after Nc6.}) 4... Nf6 (4... d6 5. Qb3 {You should probably prepare qb3 to target both the f7 pawn and the b7 pawn, should black move their bishop.}) 5. Nf3 5... Nxe4 6. Qb3 {You ignore the knight and threaten f7.} 6... Nd6 7. Bd3 {Don't let the knight take your powerful bishop.} 7... Be7 8. O-O 8... O-O 9. Re1 {After Re1, many opponents still can't resist the opportunity to play dxc3, lending you an advantage.}) (3... Nf6 4. e5 4... Nd5 (4... Qe7 5. cxd4 {cxd4 is basically forced, but at least you've made black very uncomfortable and equalized. Qe4 doesn't workbecause of Nd5.} (5. Be2 5... Qxe5 6. Nf3 6... Qa5 7. O-O 7... dxc3 8. Nxc3) (5. Nf3 {Qe4 doesn't workbecause of d3.} 5... d6)) 5. Qxd4 $1 (5. Nf3) 5... c6 6. Nf3 (6. Bc4)) (3... d3 4. Bxd3) 4. Bc4 $6 4... cxb2 (4... Nc6 5. Nf3 {Chapter: Scotch Game: Göring Gambit, Double Pawn Sacrifice} (5. Qb3) 5... Nf6 (5... cxb2 6. Bxb2) 6. O-O {Here, you are spoiled for choice. But I prefer castles, baiting black into taking the pawn.} (6. e5) (6. Qb3) (6. Nxc3) 6... Nxe4 (6... cxb2 7. Bxb2) 7. Re1 7... f5 {This enters a dazzling line where you sacrifice 8+points of material for a win.} (7... d5 8. Bxd5) 8. Nxc3 (8. Ng5) (8. Qd5) 8... Bb4 (8... Be7 9. Qd5) 9. Nxe4 (9. Qd5) 9... Bxe1 10. Bg5 10... Ne7 11. Ne5 11... Bxf2+ (11... fxe4 12. Qh5+ 12... g6 13. Bf7+) 12. Kxf2 12... fxe4 13. Qh5+ 13... g6 14. Bf7+ 14... Kf8 15. Bh6#) (4... Nf6 5. Nxc3 (5. e5) (5. Nf3) (5. Bxf7+ {VERY unsound, but it falls victim to many traps when the king stays on e7.}) 5... Bb4 6. e5 6... Ne4 (6... Qe7 7. Qe2 {unpin the pawn and force the knight back}) 7. Qd5 {Threatening checkmate on f7 and attacking the knight at the same time!} 7... Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 8... O-O 9. Qxe4) 5. Bxb2 {Chapter: Danish Gambit Accepted} 5... Bb4+ {Chapter: Danish Gambit Accepted: Copenhagen Defense} (5... Qe7 {Chapter: Danish Gambit Accepted: Chigorin Defense

The Chigorin defense: not particularly challenging. Most opponents fail to execute properly.} 6. Nc3 6... c6 7. Nf3 7... d6 (7... d5 8. Bxd5 $5 {Sacrifice the bishop! This isn't the most sound response, but it fits the spirit of the danish.} (8. Bd3 {With Bd3, mantains their objective advantage, albeit with a less exciting sacrifice.}) 8... cxd5 9. Rc1 {A mysterious looking move, but you set up a potential checkmate on c8 if white is not very careful.} 9... Nc6 (9... dxe4 10. Nd5 $3 {Leave your knight hanging and attack the queen!} 10... Qd7 $4 {amazingly, the only way to keep equality was to take the knight on f3 and sac the queen.} (10... Qd8 $3 11. Nc7+ $3 {sacrifice the knight! We either win the queen, or we checkmate in 7.}) 11. Ne5 $1 11... Qa4 12. Rxc8# {In this variation, the opponent blundered checkmate and our plan finally came to fruition. Other variations might include attacking with the rook at a3 etc.}) 10. Nxd5 10... Qxe4+ 11. Kf1 {Despite equality, this position is very hard to play for black. In fact, the only move that keeps their advantage is Bd7, but even then, black still loses their roock and the position is practically difficult.} 11... Bd7 (11... Kd8 12. Nf6+ $3 {If black tries to avoid the check by moving their king, you win their queen}) (11... Bd6 12. Bxg7 $1 {If black tries to block the fork, you take their rook.}) 12. Nc7+ 12... Kd8 13. Nxa8) 8. O-O 8... Bg4 (8... Be6 9. Nd5 $3 {Nd5! You sacrifice the knight to create a strong attack on the king.} 9... Bxd5 10. exd5 10... cxd5 11. Bb5+ (11. Qxd5) (11. Bxd5)) 9. Re1 (9. Qb3) 9... Nd7 10. Nd5 $3 {In the most common line after d6, nd5 wins the game on the spot.} 10... cxd5 11. exd5 11... Ne5 12. Bxe5 12... dxe5 13. Bb5+ {Despite the material inequality, the king is wide open. Attack accurately, and you are sure to win.} 13... Kd8 14. d6 $1 {Attack the queen.} 14... Qe6 15. Rxe5) (5... Qg5 6. Nf3 6... Qxg2 7. Bxf7+ (7. Rg1 7... Qh3 8. Bxf7+ 8... Kxf7 9. Ng5+ 9... Ke8 10. Nxh3 10... d6 11. Bxg7) 7... Kd8 8. Rg1 8... Qh3 9. Rg3 9... Qh6 10. Ng5 10... Qxh2 11. Ne6+ 11... Ke7 12. Qf3 12... dxe6 13. Ba3+ 13... Kd8 14. Bxf8) (5... Nf6 {Chapter: Danish Gambit Accepted: Classical Defense} 6. Ne2 (6. e5 6... Qe7 (6... d5 7. exf6 7... Bb4+ (7... dxc4 8. Qxd8+ 8... Kxd8 9. fxg7) 8. Bc3 8... Bxc3+ 9. Nxc3 9... dxc4 10. fxg7 10... Rg8 11. Qf3) (6... Ne4 7. Bxf7+ 7... Kxf7 8. Qd5+ 8... Ke8 9. Qxe4) 7. Qe2 7... Ng8 (7... Qb4+ 8. Bc3) 8. Nc3 8... Nc6 9. Nd5 9... Qd8 10. Nf6+ $3 10... gxf6 11. exf6+ $1 {You expose the king and win a piece. After they block, you can take with the pawn.}) (6. Nf3 6... Nxe4 7. O-O) (6. Qb3) (6. Nc3) 6... Bb4+ 7. Nbc3 7... Nxe4 (7... O-O 8. Qb3 8... Bxc3+ 9. Qxc3 {If the knight moves, you have checkmate in 1}) 8. O-O 8... Nxc3 9. Nxc3 9... Bxc3 10. Bxc3 10... O-O {After black castles, checkmate is unstoppable} 11. Qg4 11... g6 12. Qd4 12... d5 13. Qg7#) (5... d6 6. e5 {This is objectively sound, but if black takes...} (6. Nf3) 6... Be6 (6... dxe5 7. Bxf7+ 7... Ke7 8. Ba3+ 8... Kxf7 9. Qxd8) 7. Bxe6 7... fxe6 8. exd6 8... Qxd6 9. Qh5+ 9... g6 10. Qb5+ 10... c6 11. Qxb7) (5... d5 {Chapter: Danish Gambit Accepted: Schlechter Defense

A rare but unsavory attack on the bishop. Objectively winning for white.} 6. Bxd5 6... Nf6 $4 {Black, perhaps knowingly, sacrifices their queen. You must sacrifice your bishop on f7 to stay in the game.} 7. Bxf7+ $1 7... Kxf7 8. Qxd8 8... Bb4+ 9. Qd2 {if white tries to save their queen, they end up losing more material.} 9... Bxd2+ 10. Nxd2 {You have entered an equal end game. Bravo.}) (5... Bc5 6. Bxg7) (5... Nc6 6. Nf3) 6. Nc3 (6. Kf1) (6. Nd2) 6... Nf6 (6... Qe7 7. Ne2 7... Qxe4 8. Qb3) 7. Ne2 {A VERY tricky move. Black thinks they're winning material, but after the trades, the attack on the king is nearly unstoppable.} (7. Qb3 $1 7... Bxc3+ (7... Nxe4 $4 8. Bxf7+ $3 (8. Qxb4 8... Nxc3 9. Qxc3) 8... Kf8 9. Qxb4+ 9... Kxf7 10. Nxe4 {If you take back with the queen, the rook can pin.}) (7... Qe7 8. Ne2) 8. Qxc3 8... O-O (8... Nxe4 9. Bxf7+ 9... Kxf7 10. Qxg7+ {With a few more checks, you can win the knight, the rook, or the both. Be careful not to blunder the bishop to black's queen.}) 9. Nf3 {If the knight takes, you have checkmate in 1.} 9... d6 10. O-O 10... Be6 11. Bxe6 11... fxe6 12. Qb3 $1 {The queen atttacks the hanging pawn on e6 and the rook+pawn on b7}) (7. e5 7... Ne4 (7... Qe7 8. Qe2 8... Ng8) 8. Bxf7+ (8. Qd5) 8... Kxf7 9. Qd5+) 7... Nxe4 (7... O-O 8. Qb3 8... Bxc3+ 9. Qxc3 {If the knight moves, you have checkmate in 1}) 8. O-O 8... Nxc3 9. Nxc3 9... Bxc3 10. Bxc3 10... O-O {After black castles, checkmate is unstoppable} 11. Qg4 11... g6 12. Qd4 12... d5 13. Qg7# *
